metadata.name: Urban Flora #32
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Keep On #80
metadata.description:
One year ago, I published my first Fx(hash) work, "Finding my way". This piece marks its anniversary, and is intended as a THANK YOU to all the people that collected my works. 

It is based on the same algorithm as "Finding my way", i.e. a line growth animated process based on Substrate (Jared Tarbell, 2003) guided by dynamically changing vector fields made with trigonometric functions, but it uses different palettes, more vector fields, and a few more tweakings of the algorithm parameters.

The original piece was intended to symbolise a person's process of finding her/his way. Upon further reflections on the result, I think it more as representing a community process. So here is my wish for the Fx(hash) community, let's keep on finding our way.   

In what now could become a tradition, I've stolen again a palette from the beautiful work of Iskra Velitchkova.

Implemented using various packages from thi.ng/umbrella by Karsten Schmidt, AKA Toxi

metadata.name: reborn #12
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Tessellum #14
metadata.description:
Tessellum can be understood as a sophisticated form of tessellation that combines repetitive geometric patterns with spatial coherence and depth. In an artistic context, it suggests a structured configuration where each component interlocks precisely, creating a seamless, continuous design. This term embodies not only visual repetition but also a sense of order and interconnectedness, where patterns are arranged in such a way that they convey both structural complexity and a harmonious, multidimensional effect.

The **Tessellum** project is essentially a unique cube. It’s a cube that has other cubes on each of its faces, arranged in such a way that they do not collide with each other. It can be described as a combination of cubes of various sizes, forming the final image. In this project, you can rotate the main cube as you wish by clicking and holding the left mouse button.
this project available in both TEZ&ETH

metadata.name: Primitifs systématiques #90
metadata.description:
Primitifs systématiques is the first generative instalment of David Umemoto’s studies of space and volume. Placed at the crux of brutalism and minimalism, these structures based on the original stackable concrete piece Primitif 04 evoke impossible paths yet to be explored. 

The original Primitif 04 has been both preserved and dented, conserved and enhanced. It is still here. But it cannot be found, only encountered. Throughout your explorations of the Primitifs systématiques, you will find that its original shapes have been multiplied, rotated, re-ordered to create new structures. After spending some time exploring its paths, when you stop looking for it, you will realize that 04 is still here, intact.

Lines of work chosen for this piece also draw a perspective. The orientation of the primitives pulls directly towards an intense source of light. Sometimes it is visible, sometimes it is not. This perfect alignment is a call to life. They who look at the sunrise with relief cannot be anything but hopeful. But how can we project life on a concrete behemoth? Stand long enough in front of it, and you too will see that we have no choice but to.

----

Primitifs systématiques is the generative art genesis piece of David Umemoto. It was built in collaboration with Anaglyphic. It is the first collaborative spatial token made available on the anaver.se.

metadata.name: f-emerald #222
metadata.description:
f-emerald generates unique ephemeral crystal-like structures that morph in space. each generation has a different shape, animation and colour palette. 

the crystals flicker with colours in the dark most of the time. there is, however, a 20% chance of obtaining a crystal on a bright background with a light colour palette and one out of ten structures is created in black and white.

metadata.name: Organic Diffusion #152
metadata.description:
Organic diffusion, a silent guide,
Through the veils of chaos, we abide.
In the microscopic realm, secrets unfold,
A journey of mystery, yet untold...

Display : Organic diffusion adapts by default to any screen, with an artwork changing depending on width and height (while maintaining the same parameters). In Vertical mode, the artwork displayed will be the captured (preview) one. Meant to be displayed on walls for an extended period, allowing enjoyment of the ever-changing artwork...

First minter gets 25% of royalties.

Options :
p to pause/unpause
s to save
1, 2, ... to increase the resolution (3 to get 3000pixels in height, etc...)
c to capture the same preview
d to toggle display between fullscreen and vertical (4:3)
+/- to increase/decrease details
z to zoom-in
f to increase some speed
v to start/stop the webm video capture
a in live view will allow to capture the 1000 seeds in low res images to help you choose your favorites

metadata.name: Murked Being #81
metadata.description:
This artwork was part of experimentation to create a figure that implements the pareidolia effect with feedback modulation and other manipulation using the Hydra library. The visual appearance was inspired by Banaspati, one of many ghostly entities in Indonesia that looks like a floating fireball. The being was visualized to look as it was formed from blazing dark smoke with some parts showing sharp-subtle shapes, colors, and textures, creating a sense of abstract-ghoulish expression that is murked in its impression.

Move your mouse up and down to rotate the eyes and the hidden animation on its head.  Made using Hydra (https://hydra.ojack.xyz/)

Rangga Purnama Aji, 2022
https://linktr.ee/ranggapuraji
